rnal problems stemmed partly from the department store market where an attempt by revlon to economize by grouping its ritz monteil and borghese prestige brands at one counter failed other problems included the introduction of no sweat a deodorant which despite its  million introductory advertising budget failed to garner market share the reformulation of flex a popular shampoo which lost market share when revlon introduced a new formula with new packaging and a higher price and a  percent shrinkage in the fragrance market that affected the entire industry turning the corner in mids by  revlon held only  percent of the us massmarket cosmetics market losses were mounting year after year thanks in large part to the money that had to be spent each year to service the debt in  alone  million went toward debt service contributing to an operating loss of  million  million of which stemmed from extraordinary restructuring charges perelman was forced to sell still more assets to keep revlon from defaulting on its loans in addition to selling  percent of national health laboratories by  perelman had to also sell off some assets from the core cosmetics area in  max factor and betrix were sold to procter  gamble for  billion in cash sold off the following year were the highend halston and princess marcella borghese brands unfortunately for perelman such moves were not enough to gain the confidence of wall street in  perelman tried to sell  million shares of revlon stock in an initial public offering ipo at about  to  per share the ipo failed a victim of a sluggish stock market poor revlon earnings and the huge debt that continued to weigh down the cosmetics giant to shore up sagging sales revlon ceo jerry levin boosted revlons advertising budget by  percent in  to  million much of this money was spent on television advertising with less spent on print ads and instore promotions than in the past while the revlon line was promoted in this fashion and through massmarket retailers 